description: Bling delete '65 'Stang for sale.  When Ford designed the original Mustang, they created a compact, sporty American car that was fun to drive.  It literally started the Pony car movement.  This particular car takes a super clean, stripped down approach to the presentation, and it looks great!

Fastback styling wasn't that common at the time the Mustang was introduced, but the style has proven popular through time, and looks better today than ever.  This particular one takes a minimalist approach to the look by removing most of the chrome, brightwork, and badging.   There are only two emblems on the car and they were carefully chosen.  First, you gotta have the running Mustang leading the way on the grill, so it's there in all its glory.  Then the gas cap sits nicely in the middle of a blacked out rear panel with no chrome around the taillights, and has only a small Pony in the center of it.  Sweet!  Then, they sprayed the whole car a bright white that really looks sharp.  That includes the bumpers which they treated and painted white too.   It almost looks like a 1965 prototype version of the new Mustangs with their body color bumpers.  A black GT stripe graces the rocker panel, and Torq Thrust wheels give the car a ready for action look.

Open the door and you will find a black interior, but they left the chrome alone here.  And it looks good that way.  A chrome strip on the door panel compliments the polished door handle and window crank.  The front buckets have a big, bold, piece of chrome which is actually structural.  I mean, why hide it when it can look that good?  The hatchbacks have a nice feature in the fold down rear seat, so you can treat this car like it's a 2-seat sports car if you wish.  Set yourself down in the driver's seat and grab a hold of the Pilot 4 spoke steering wheel, then reach for the Hurst T-handle shifter which falls right to hand.  That deep cowl dashboard has the speedo and engine gauges easily visible in front of the driver, and a glove box off to the right.  The radio is in the center backed up by big Kenwood speakers in the kick panels.

The engine and drivetrain on this car reinforce the stripped down, ready for action look of the body.  Pop the hood and you will find a 289-cubic inch motor with a chrome air topper and ''Powered by Ford'' valve covers.  It is equipped with MSD ignition, long tube headers, and Flowmaster mufflers.  It sounds healthy because it is healthy.  A 4-speed manual trans is always fun to stir around and is perfect for sporting around twisty backroads or launching off the line at the strip.  Sports cars demand a capable suspension, and you will find that here too.  A Monte Carlo bar helps reinforce the shock towers against the forces generated during spirited driving, and there is a healthy sway bar to help keep the car cornering flat while doing it.  Heavy duty shocks handle the bumps and dips, and front disc brakes provide the whoa power to haul this pony down from speed.    The rubber meets the road through 215/60R15 tires all around mounted on those sweet Torq Thrust wheels.
Stripped down, powered up, and fun to drive.  Come on down, check it out, then take it home and start having fun with it.

The Ford Mustang is an American car manufactured by Ford. It was originally based on the platform of the second generation North American Ford Falcon, a compact car. The original 1962 Ford Mustang I two-seater concept car had evolved into the 1963 Mustang II four-seater concept car which Ford used to pretest how the public would take interest in the first production Mustang. The 1963 Mustang II concept car was designed with a variation of the production model's front and rear ends with a roof that was 2.7 inches shorter. Introduced early on April 17, 1964 (16 days after the Plymouth Barracuda), and thus dubbed as a ''1964½'' by Mustang fans, the 1965 Mustang was the automaker's most successful launch since the Model A. The Mustang has undergone several transformations to its current sixth generation.

While all 1965 Ford Mustangs are iconic, this one is also built with an extra dose of eye-catching character.  With the GT-inspired touches, interesting paint, low mileage, and an upgraded A/C interior, it's the distinguished pony car for people who love driving their classics.

There are plenty of nice red Mustangs out there, so we tend to take notice when someone takes the time to invest in a respray of original shade of K-code Smoke Silver Gray.  It has the kind of gloss and shine that can be a standout in a crowd.  But more than just paint, it's a true '65 Mustang – the kind of American icon that evokes memories the moment anyone catches sight of the pony on the grille.  So it's hard to go wrong with this classic coupe.  Every piece of brightwork is complete and near pristine - from the wide front bumper, to the door handles, to the Mustang-branded gas cap.  Completing this iconic appearance are the GT-style upgrades like the fog lights in the grille and the dual exhaust mounted through the rear valance.  It even has the cool side scoops of the coveted California Special.  Finishing off the extra sporty package are the styled steel wheels with cool redline tires.

Inside, this one has some great standout touches. It starts with the factory-correct blue seats.  It's a terrific complementing color to the exterior gray, so this was ordered from day one to be a great coordinating total package.  Plus, you have all the right iconic touches – from the dual cowl dash, to the correct mat in the trunk.  And there are plenty of nice upgrades to this classic package to make it a great cruising machine.  The cup holder center console, AM/FM/cassette stereo, and ice-cold R134a air conditioning means this is a classic in which everyone will want to go for a ride.  But even when you're just driving solo, this pony car is built to make sure you have the best features. The upgraded wood-rimmed steering wheel and large VDO tach are instant indications this is a true driver's classic.

The 289 cubic-inch motor's trusty and powerful reputation is only enhanced on this freshly rebuilt example.  The V8's presentation lives up to the sporty exterior with a large Cobra air topper and matching Shelby valve covers.  Plus, the polished braces and addition of a Monte Carlo bar really adds a nice dose of speedy flash.  This V8 backs up its enhanced performance appearance by inhaling deeply through a Holley four-barrel carburetor.  And it exhales through headers that add power as they as contribute to the growl of the dual exhaust.  To complement the added performance, this pony car features a three-speed automatic transmission with 2,200 RPM stall, a newer steering box, and upgraded bushings.

Complete with maintenance records and the owner's manual, you're looking at a vintage Mustang that has received all the right investments to be a looker and a driver.  So if you're been searching for an icon, don't miss this one.  Call today!!!

Lee Iacocca and Ford changed the automotive landscape at the New York World's Fair in 1964. Many believe that no car in history, other than maybe the Model T, affected the way Americans perceive automobiles like the Mustang. This 1966 Mustang coupe is an older restoration and a nice example of this American icon. The body was refinished in Sahara Beige. Period correct Mustang GT wheels, redline BFG radials and a GT fog light package give the exterior a nice look. The interior was reupholstered in beige vinyl - door cards, headliner, carpeting and wheel are all in good condition. The factory dash houses a full gauge package and an AM/FM sound system. Based on the VIN, this was a factory 'C' code car - a 289ci/200hp 2V. Engine casting numbers show the block to be a 289ci motor cast in 1966. It runs an Edelbrock aluminum intake with a Holley 4160 carburetor. Matched with the 4-speed manual gearbox, this is a nice performance package. With a Blue Oval dress-up kit it looks and sounds great. Brakes are 4-wheel manual drum units. This is a nice 4-speed Mustang coupe that will quickly find a new home. ALL VEHICLES SOLD ''AS IS''.

Here's an A-code 1965 Ford Mustang with a distinct exterior, upgraded A/C interior, and a nice V8 under the hood. So this is the one for those who want a memorable icon.

Wimbledon White is a great factory-correct color to have on a Mustang.  But what makes this one really standout is that this very continental color is enhanced by some sophisticated features.  After all, with the newer black vinyl top and wire wheel covers, this coupe has a bit of upper-class distinction.  Plus, the GT-style fog lights in the grille adds a sporty allure to this A-code car.

We love it when a vinyl top is also a preview of the interior color.  And this one does it particularly well with an investment in fresh materials and nice upgrades.  So the black bucket seats up front feel fresh, and they have the comfortable addition of headrests. In-between is a modern center console with comfy armrest and cup holders.  The radio looks like a factory piece, but it's upgraded retrosound unit with a digital tuner and an aux input for the most modern music players.  The three-spoke steering wheel gives you that classic grippy feeling you expect from a Mustang, but beyond that, a crisp set of TPI gauges keep you better informed than the factory setup ever did.  But your favorite upgrade will likely be the R134a air conditioning.  After all, that will keep you feeling as cool as you look.

Under the hood, the 289 cubic-inch V8 looks great with its bright air topper and ribbed Mustang valve covers.  This motor inhales deeply from an Edelbrock four-barrel, which give it a more modern carb while still staying true to its A-code nature.  The belts, wires, and hoses tell you this is a nicely maintained engine bay, and the sound of the dual exhaust reminds you why a V8 Mustang is always in demand.  Plus, this one has some great anytime driving features like the three-speed automatic transmission, power steering, and front disc brakes.
Complete with owner's manual, here's an icon with all the right upgrades.  So if you're ready for a pony with all the right distinction, call today!
